---
description: Author and validate changed Vanessa feature files through Vanessa UI MCP
agent: code
---

Use this command only from an active `itldev/*` worktree. This is an interactive authoring gate, never an `itl-routine` action.

1. Read `.agents/skills/1c-workflow/references/vanessa-tests.md` and `references/vanessa-authoring.md`, then run the helper. For changed features it updates the copied branch infobase before starting MCP:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\.agents\skills\1c-workflow\scripts\agent-1c.ps1 -Action prepare-vanessa-authoring
```

2. Read `.agent-1c/vanessa-authoring/state.json`. For `skipped`, `not-required`, or a fresh `passed`, report that result and stop. For `ready`, use `itl-vanessa-ui` `call_tool`; its branch-local backend starts on the first inner call without client reload. Never call the private backend through raw HTTP.
3. For every changed feature, pass these known inner names to `call_tool` in order, with only their explicitly intended arguments; do not call `resolve_tool` first:
   `search_for_steps_by_keywords` → `open_feature_file` → `check_syntax` → `get_info_about_line_scenario` → `run_scenario` → `get_test_results`.
   The search call accepts only `search_name`, `search_description`, `search_type`, `exclude_name`, `exclude_description`, `exclude_type`, and `limit`; never invent `keywords`. A KB or reference-suite match is not proof that a step is exposed by the current Vanessa runtime.
4. Fix the feature and repeat the relevant MCP checks until the changed scenarios pass. Then finish through the helper so MCP state and client config are cleaned up:

```powershell
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File .\.agents\skills\1c-workflow\scripts\agent-1c.ps1 -Action complete-vanessa-authoring -AuthoringResult passed
```

For a terminal authoring failure, call the same action with `-AuthoringResult failed -AuthoringErrorCategory <category>` where category is `unsupported-step`, `scenario-context`, `product-assertion`, or `runner`. Do not use this MCP run as final verification; run `/itl-check` after a successful authoring pass.
